Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Afribank, East African Breweries Move

-- B y   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a   a n d   J o h n s t o n e   O l e   T u r a n a
-- 
2011-02-21T15:41:37Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-21/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-afribank-east-african-breweries-move.html
Kenya’s All-Share Index dropped to
the lowest since July 29, retreating 1.3 percent to 76.83 by the
3 p.m. close in Nairobi.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index declined for a fourth day, losing
0.2 percent to close at 2,055.61 by 1:30 p.m. in  Port Louis .
Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index  climbed for a third
day, adding 0.3 percent to 26,709.63 by 2:31 p.m. in Lagos,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg. Namibia’s FTSE  Namibia
Overall Index  snapped four days of decreases, adding 0.9 percent
to close at 907.04 by 5 p.m. in Windhoek. The Ghana Stock
Exchange Composite Index slipped 0.7 percent to close at 1,044.4
by 3 p.m. in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.    Afribank Nigeria Plc  (AFRIBANK NL), a lender bailed out by
the country’s central bank in 2009, climbed 12 kobo, or 4.7
percent, to 2.69 naira, the biggest jump since Feb. 2. Vine
Alliance will sign an accord with the bank to buy it,
BusinessDay reported, without saying how it got the information.    East African Breweries Ltd . (EABL KN), Diageo Plc’s Kenyan
unit, fell to the lowest level in more than five months,
dropping 7 shillings, or 3.7 percent, to 182 shillings.  Net income fell to 3.19 billion shillings ($39.2 million)
in the six months through December, from 3.49 billion shillings
a year earlier, Nairobi-based EABL said in a statement
distributed by the city’s stock exchange on Feb. 18.    Intercontinental Bank Plc  (INTERCON NL), a Nigerian lender,
climbed for a second day, adding 7 kobo, or 2.8 percent, to 2.6
naira. Access Bank Plc will invest in Intercontinental,
BusinessDay reported today, without saying how it got the
information.    Oceanic Bank International Plc  (OCEANIC NL), a Nigerian
lender, surged the most since Feb. 10, rallying 14 kobo, or 4.7
percent, to 3.12 naira.  First Bank of Nigeria Plc  will sign an
agreement to buy a stake in the lender that was bailed out by
the central bank in 2009, BusinessDay reported today, without
saying how it got the information.  To contact the reporters on this story:
